# Review routing by scope/type (docs/issues/0020, PRD.md R24: "CODEOWNERS
# routes reviews by scope/type"). Standard GitHub/GitLab CODEOWNERS syntax:
# later patterns win over earlier ones on overlapping paths, so the general
# org-tier rule sits first and the more specific type/config rules sit after
# it. This file is NOT a record (packages/core/src/discoverRecords.ts only
# discovers `.md` files under org/, products/<slug>/, teams/<slug>/) — it
# never enters the catalog and `lore validate` never inspects it; it only
# configures the git host's PR review requirement. See README.md
# "`.lore/` configuration" / "Review routing" for the full convention.

# Org-tier records (org/*, excluding org/type/ below) default to the
# architecture group — org-scope knowledge is cross-cutting by definition.
/org/**                        @architecture

# The type catalog (org/type/) and Lore's own deployment configuration
# (.lore/) are platform-level surfaces: changing what counts as a valid
# record type, or the identity/grant model itself, is a platform change
# regardless of which scope's contributor opened the PR.
/org/type/**                   @platform-maintainers
/.lore/**                      @platform-maintainers
/CODEOWNERS                    @platform-maintainers

# Product-tier records route to that product's own reviewers. Placeholder
# alias pattern below — add one line per product as products/ grows, replacing
# <product-slug> with the real directory name (e.g. products/acme/**).
# /products/<product-slug>/**  @product-<product-slug>-team
/products/acme/**               @product-acme-team

# Team-tier records route to that team's own reviewers. Placeholder alias
# pattern below — add one line per team as teams/ grows, replacing <team-slug>
# with the real directory name (e.g. teams/platform/**).
# /teams/<team-slug>/**        @team-<team-slug>
